<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4421">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4421">
This species is easily recognizable by the subdimorphic leaves and orangish glands present on receptacle (
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, A. R." journalOrPublisher="University of California Publications in Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" pagination="1 - 38" title="Taxonomy of ThelypterissubgenusSteiropteris, including Glaphyropteris (Pteridophyta)" volume="76" year="1980">Smith 1980</bibRefCitation>
). The closest species appears to be 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Centricae" family="Chironomidae" genus="T." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="T. (Steiropteris) leprieurii" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" phylum="Diatomeae" rank="species" species="leprieurii" subGenus="Steiropteris">T. (Steiropteris) leprieurii</taxonomicName>
(Hook.) R.M.Tryon, which can also present dimorphic fronds (
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, A. R." journalOrPublisher="University of California Publications in Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" pagination="1 - 38" title="Taxonomy of ThelypterissubgenusSteiropteris, including Glaphyropteris (Pteridophyta)" volume="76" year="1980">Smith 1980</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
